content.excerpt: Finnish companies are getting support for internationalisation into emerging markets.

Tekes – the Finnish Funding Agency for Technology and Innovation has granted Aalto University’s ‘The New Global’ project EUR 1.8 million in funding in connection with the application round for big strategic research openings. The New Global is a multidisciplinary action research project with the aim of co-creating frugal innovations for large low-income emerging markets while creating new business opportunities for Finnish companies. When adapted to the developed economies (reverse innovation), these innovations may be disruptive and very price competitive.

By 2050 the world's five largest economic powers will be China, the United States, India, Brazil and Mexico. The rapid population and economic growth in emerging markets is expected to result in a powershift also with respect to innovation capacity. Increasing scarcity of natural resources, combined with a growing middle class in emerging markets, will push forward future sustainable and affordable solutions (frugal innovations).

The successful countries in the reorganisation of the global economy will be those that adapt to the new global situation. Aalto University's The New Global project will help Finnish companies co-create innovations in emerging markets, especially in India, Brazil, Mexico, Tanzania and South Africa.

Until now it has been difficult for Finnish companies to create innovations for the needs of the world’s urban growth centres. Small and medium-sized companies in particular often suffer from a lack of information, experience and reliable partners, and from insufficient pilot projects.The New Global offers participating companies the possibility to acquire information and experience on doing innovation in emerging markets,’ says the project's director, Professor Minna Halme of the Aalto University School of Business.

Developed markets can no longer be considered the centre of internationalisation. What is needed instead is the creation of completely new markets countries with large emerging markets. Finnish companies are clearly behind those in Denmark and the Netherlands in these endeavours. The risk is that we might be left behind in the ongoing economic change. Especially in emerging large low-income markets, often called the base of the pyramid, the operating logic is different from that in developed markets. The informal sector has a big share, which means that learning new operating models is a prerequisite for successful business pois sana, Professor Halme adds.
